title: Iron Brain: The Rebirth
description:
PG-13 version of the popular convention game.
Contestants attempt to keep a straight face while reading aloud some of the worst dreck ever to stain a page.

title: SF writing, critical praise and winning awards
people: PRK , Stephen Dedman, Mihaela Marija Perkovic, Juliet Marillier, Ian Nichols, Charles Stross, Lucy Sussex
description: Panellists discuss the type of genre writing that gathers critical attention, literary buzz and award-winning momentum.

title: Introduction to the Perth LARP scene
people: Sam Bowden, Andrew Leitch, Tim Pullen
description: Live Action Roleplaying Games (or LARPs) and the vibrant Perth scene that plays them. Meet representatives from various Perth LARP groups who will talk about their games, where they happen, what is involved, etc.

title: MTV animation of the 90s - a retrospective
description: From the end of the 1980s to the early 2000s, MTV introduced a number of animated shows to their lineup which would gain a cult following and become collectively known to fans as "90s MTV Animation". Often surreal, frequently funny and generally possessed of an independent spirit, many of these series were highly acclaimed and several served as springboards to bigger work for their burgeoning creators. This presentation will provide a brief overview of the primary releases of the era - Liquid Television, The Head, The Maxx, Aeon Flux, Daria and, yes, even Beavis and Butthead.

title: Write a role playing campaign in two hours
description: Come and learn how to write a role playing campaign in two hours...in two hours.

title: Engaging with Social Media as a professional writer
people: John Birmingham, Gail Simone, Charles Stross, Lucy Sussex
description: The Guests of Honour discuss their experiences as professional writers in a constantly changing online environments of social media and the digital environment.

title: Nineteenth Century Fantasy Art Nudes
description: A presentation followed by a discussion on the use of fantasy figures in nineteenth-century nude oils and watercolours. Images of gods and goddesses, mermaids, sirens, nymphs and satyrs are examined.

title: London Worldcon 2014
description: How to get to it, what to do, where to stay.

title: Video Quiz
description: The 7th annual video quiz is back with clips from the world of music, film and TV and clips celebrate 50 years of Doctor Who.

title: The legacy of Quatermass
description: 60 years after the first installment of the ground breaking series, we look back on its legacy as the inspiration for everything from Doctor Who plots and hit films, through to its impact on procedural TV shows.

title: Educational futurism
people: Dave Cake, Chris Creagh, Gina Goddard
description: The flipped classroom, Khan academy, and TED - looking back on science fiction predictions in the field of education and what has come to pass.

title: The history of Ghibli
description: In recent years we were made aware of the History of Disney with all its complexity, now we move on to what many would call “Disney of the East”. Come hear all about the early years of Studio Ghibli’s works and what went into creating the company that it is today.

title: Music of geeky things
description: Can you imagine the final scene of 'A New Hope' without music? Did you notice the difference in that episode of 'Buffy' that didn't have any music? Music is the great accompaniment to many Movies, TV shows and Computer games. Come join Andy and John (Parker) for a musical celebration of......well......music.

title: Lost Girl - a discussion
people: , , John Parker , Helen Duffill, Jennifer Gladwell
description: Panel discussion of the moral, mythological and sexual ambiguities within the hit Canadian television series.

title: 20 minutes sideways: Urban Fantasy
people: , , Helen Duffill, Katherine McFarlane, Charles Stross, Lucy Sussex
description: Urban fantasy is selling fast. Our panellists interrogate its appeal.

title: Whose future is this anyway?
people: , , John Birmingham, Chris Creagh, Elaine Kemp, Charles Stross
description: Eighty years after a Brave New World, almost thirty years after 1984 and A Handmaid's Tale and twenty years after Fukuyama's End of History thesis, our panel discuss the way in which fictional and theoretical landscapes are increasingly reassembling our reality. We ask, which future are we living in, or most likely to live in?

title: Bond after Skyfall
people: John Birmingham, Michael Cogan, Matt Holmes, Damian Magee
description: Discussion of the recent James Bond film, it's plot and themes, and where it leaves the Bond setting for new installments.

title: Homework panel
description: Discussion of Swancon 2014's guests of honour, their works, what to read and watch and see and do before next year's convention, etc.

title: Swancon 2013 Masquerade: Remix
description:
“Remix”

It’s time to get creative. Think of a character, any character. Or think of two and mix them together. Reimagine them. Genderswap them. Take them to a different time, culture or genre. Give them a new look or a new personality. Do whatever you want. There are no rules except this – take something recognisable and change it.

We look forward to seeing what imaginative costumes our attendees can conceive. The SwanCon 2013 Masquerade Ball promises to be a fun-filled evening of cosplay, music, revelry and great company, so get cracking and make sure you look the part!

title: Swancon 2014 Launch
description: Launch of Swancon 2014.

title: The Devil in the Radio
description: An exploration of the dark, macabre, disturbing and grim in music. From goth to black metal to thoroughly twisted - music and discussion (This panel is not suitable for children.)

title: Femme Noir: women detective stories
description: Exploring the world of female-written detective stories.

title: The Disney Renaissance: Fresh Blood in the House of Mouse
description:
In 1981 Walt Disney Pictures released The Fox and the Hound, the first animated feature produced by the company without the participation of either Walt Disney himself or the “nine old men” with whom he had revolutionised animation in the 1930s and 1940s. This new generation of animators and filmmakers – including John Lassetter, Brad Bird, Ron
Clements, John Musker and Tim Burton – would revolutionise Disney animation over the following decade, and forever change the art and business of the Hollywood movie.
This solo presentation explores the art and making of nine animated feature films, from 1981’s The Fox and the Hound to 1994’s The Lion King, a period widely referred to as “the Disney renaissance”.

title: Birds of Prey
people: Damian Magee, Gail Simone, Zoe Wadsworth
description: A discussion of the many female characters within the Detective Comics Universe, both classic and New 52 reboot continuity-based.

title: Doctor Who: the 20th season
people: Damian Magee, Heather Magee, Danny Oz, Grant Watson
description: This panel looks at Peter Davison's season which includes Snakedance, The Guardian Trilogy,and The Five Doctors.

title: Can you swing a halberd - realism in gaming
people: Andrew Hahn, Colm Kiely, Andrew Leitch
description:
Which games emphasise realism and real-world information in their rules? Can more realistic rules sets be more fun? 
The panellists explores the use of realism and breaks with realism in gaming.

title: Analog gaming in a digital world
people: Rob Masters, Tim McDougall, Alicia Smith, Danica Zuks
description: Exploring the introduction of tablets, mobile apps, and gaming elements into modern board games, and new avenues of fund-raising and development. Looking at the rise of Kickstarter and other crowd-sourced fundraising avenues and how this is improving development of games.

title: Old school roleplaying
description: Looking at old school roleplaying games and checking the hobby's life signs. Has the resurgence of retro-gaming helped or hindered in the long run?

people: Sophie Ambrose, Lee Battersby, Jeremy Byrne
description: Exploring the evolving and expanding world of interactive stories, from text adventures and dating sims to Myst and Mass Effect. What makes them compelling, why they don't always work, and how to create your own."

people: Doug Burbridge, Chris Creagh, Cathy Cupitt, Elaine Kemp

title: Fairy tales: a grim resurgence

In a time of rapid technological and social change is the future off limits?
Examining the arguements for and against.

title: Doctor Who, companion(ship) and the new dynamic
people: Aaron Creaser, Helen Duffill, Kathleen Griffiths, Nancy Lorenz, Damian Magee, Samara Morgan, Candice Schilder
description: Examining the evolving roles, portrayals and agency of companions in the recent Doctor Who series.

title: Australian Young Adult Fiction
description: An appreciation of the work of three authors writing genre fiction for the young adult market.

title: Superhero Comics: Rebooting and Relaunching the Multiverse(s)
people: Gail Simone, Emily Smith, Grant Watson
description:
In September 2011 DC Comics relaunched the entire line of superhero comics, to tremendous financial success. In 2012 Marvel followed suit, with their rolling Marvel Now relaunch of many of their key titles and characters. 
What has been the ultimate effect of these efforts to renew interest in comic books? Are the comics better than they were before, or worse?
What are the highlights and lowlights? 
What can the industry learn from the experience for when it inevitably happens
again?

title: Filking

title: Anime Long-form - negotiating the never-ending battles
people: Andrew Hahn, Damian Magee, Candice Schilder
description:
Some anime (Japanese animated films and television series) runs for as little as 30 minutes. Some run for six episodes. Some run for 13, or 26. Then there are those other shows: the really, really long ones.
Naruto is 220 episodes long. Bleach has 336. Pokémon is still running after 750, and Doraemon has nearly reached 1,800.
Is there a strategy to watching long-running anime? Are there episodes you can watch or skip? Do any of these series justify their length? A panel of anime enthusiasts discuss their favourite (and least favourite) long-running series, and attempt to identify the secret to their success.

title: All in the manual - writing realism and technology into your fiction
people: John Birmingham, Ian Nichols, Charles Stross
description:
What responsibility do speculative fiction writers have towards realism in their work? Where do writers turn for information to ground their future technologies in reality? How much can be hand-waved away, and how much should be properly researched? 
Should all science fiction use believable science? Why can an audience accept Indiana Jones nearly getting his heart ripped out by magic, or meeting a centuries-old knight, but can’t accept him surviving a nuclear explosion by hiding
inside a refrigerator? What measures should writers take to make their works feel real for their audience – and what responsibility does the reader have to accept what the writers presents to them?

description: H.P. Lovecraft's Cthulhu Mythos and the various tropes and elements it introduced is a rich but complicated legacy of resources for horror and fantasy writers to explore. A discussion of how writers adapt and repurpose elements of the Mythos to create new works.

Unfortunately she couldn't be here to talk to us in person but she's giving us the next best thing - a video Q&A. Before the convention, Cherie took questions from Swancon members and recorded this video just for us. Over the course of 45 minutes Cherie discusses her writing, the state of Steampunk, alternate history and the joys of pet ownership. Tune in!

title: The Haunting of Lucy Sussex
description: Lucy Sussex takes us through her experiences researching historical identities and some of the darker chapters in Australian history.

title: Hidden History and Unsolved Crimes
people: John Birmingham, Charles Stross, Lucy Sussex
description: Famous historical crimes and conspiracies are often the subject of fascination in part because they are unsolved and so a sense of mystery remains. Famous unsolved crimes, or crimes that retain a whiff of conspiracy and the unexplained, are often the subject of fiction, such as Jack The Ripper and the Kennedy Assassination. How do you deal with this as an author, and what is your responsibility to a true represention of history?

title: Lucy Sussex Presents The Cautionary Tale of Fergus Hume
description: How do you write one of the best-selling novels of your age and still not make any money? Lucy Sussex explores the life and times of Fergus Hume, his best-selling crime fiction, and his dabblings in fantasy, utopia, apocalyptic fiction and fairytales. Hume will be the subject of Sussex's next book, so come along to get a sneak preview of her latest work.

title: Madman Screenings
description: Tune in for some of the best Anime Madman Entertainment has to offer.

title: Rebel Empire Workshops Interactive show
description: Wanted to know what the Imperium of Rebel Empire Workshops get up to during training? Rebel Empire Workshops is on its 5th year and many things have grown in that time. From new Members to new Characters to Costumes and Props and of course Fight Choreography. So come and watch (possibly join in) as the R.E.W. cast and Crew put on a performance of improvisational fun and entertainment for all fans; young and old.

title: Rebel Empire Workshops NERF Games 2013
description:
Come and join in some NERF Gun fun with the REW Imperium! From the iddy-bitty single shooters to the big full automatics to NERF Wii Games there will be a game for all. Whether you are new to NERF guns or not, it will be guaranteed to be full of laughter and excitement.
There will be a gold coin donation before entry to this event. For those willing to participate, there will be  NERF prizes and to be won for each game!

title: Discovering story games
description: Story games have been the subject of much innovation in game design over the past decade. From their beginnings in The Extraordinary Adventures of Baron Munchausen until now, game developers have explored a wide range of techniques to create systems that will produce engaging and entertaining stories. This panel will discuss some of the history of story games and how they move the players between collaborative story makers, audience, and performers. After the panel look for demonstrations of the games in the gaming room.

title: Trailer Park

description: Screening and discussion of the latest genre movie trailers.

title: 2012 in film
description: 2012 was a big year for film - a Dark Knight Rose (for the third and final time), some Avengers assembled and one adventurous Hobbit went on an Unexpected Journey. Tom and Tina will once again revisit the big cinematic releases of the past year and share their thoughts.

title: Writing Alternative History
description: Come hear two of our Guests of Honour discuss their experiences creating alternate-history, parallel universe and near future series worlds and the inspirations that drive them.

title: Visions of Political Control Through Environmental Design
description: Since the 1970’s, Crime Prevention Through Environmental Design (CPTED) has been seen as a way of increasing the safety of the community by reducing property and violent crime. But what happens when speaking in opposition to the government or to associating with individuals who hold a different political view is defined as a crime? This presentation explores three early Twentieth Century dystopian novels in which a central authoritarian government rules its population with an iron fist and crushes any opposition within its own population. Part of the narrative of each of these novels is the use of the principles of CPTED as a way of preventing and detecting political dissent (state-lead political violence). The presenters propose that this evil twin of CPTED could be called Political Control Through Environmental Design (PCTEP).
